---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Framework"
  description="The complete missional product design framework — nine principles for building technology that serves spiritual formation."
>
  <div class="container">
    <section class="section">
      <h1>The Missional Product Design Framework</h1>
      <p class="text-muted" style="max-width: none; font-size: 1.1rem;">
        A comprehensive guide to building digital tools that serve spiritual formation and human flourishing.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- Nine Principles In Depth -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>The Nine Principles</h2>

      <article class="principle mt-xl">
        <h4>1. Design for actual engagement patterns</h4>
        <p>
          Ambient and receptive modes first, not assumed deep study. The dominant mode is reactive, situational, and
          brief. Audio is the fastest-growing format. Reading plans fail at 50% dropout. A next-generation app must make
          ambient and receptive engagement first-class citizens.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>2. Multimodal formation</h4>
        <p>
          Audio, music, contemplative silence, and guided practice as primary formats, not supplements to reading. The
          Christian tradition has always formed through multiple modes; digital tools should recover that breadth.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>3. Resist spiritual commodification</h4>
        <p>
          Transparent tradition sourcing, depth over browsing, communal accountability. Name traditions (Ignatian,
          Benedictine, Franciscan, Orthodox). Encourage commitment to a single practice for sustained periods rather than
          daily sampling.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>4. Serve communal as well as individual formation</h4>
        <p>
          Design for shared engagement and social context. Individual practice disconnected from community risks
          consumerism. Structural prompts toward communal engagement counter the privatization tendency.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>5. Scaffold toward community without requiring it</h4>
        <p>
          Liminal users cannot be told to "find a church"; build bridges, don't create prerequisites. Begin alone, develop
          spiritual rhythm, then grow toward embodied community.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>6. Grace-based mechanics throughout</h4>
        <p>
          No default streaks, shame triggers, or social comparison. Opt-in accountability. The ethical line is consent:
          the user choosing tools for their own formation, not the platform deploying mechanics for its retention. The
          animating question: does this serve freedom or fear? Grace or guilt? Formation or metrics?
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>7. European-specific defaults</h4>
        <p>
          Privacy-first architecture, multi-tradition hospitality, post-Christian assumptions, GDPR as dignity commitment.
          A European spiritual app cannot localize an American product wholesale.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>8. Serve the spiritually liminal</h4>
        <p>
          Guide through personalized companionship, not overwhelming libraries. The liminal user asking "where do I start?"
          needs a companion who listens, not a catalog that searches.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>9. Formation metrics over engagement metrics</h4>
        <p>
          Measure depth and freedom, not daily active users and streak completions. If the app doesn't serve growth, users
          cancel — and that's the point.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Tensions Section -->
  <section class="section-alt section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Core Tensions</h2>
      <p>These principles live in productive tension. Understanding these tensions helps navigate design decisions:</p>

      <article class="principle mt-xl">
        <h4>Brief Engagement vs. Commodification</h4>
        <p>
          Supporting ambient, brief engagement (Principle 1) risks encouraging spiritual window-shopping without depth.
          Counter this by honoring tradition sources (Principle 3) and encouraging sustained commitment to single practices
          rather than daily sampling.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>Community Requirement vs. Liminal Reality</h4>
        <p>
          Deep Christian formation happens in community (Principle 4), but many users start alone and outside traditional
          church (Principle 8). The solution: scaffold toward community without requiring it (Principle 5). Build bridges
          for liminal users who may eventually find embodied community.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>Regular Practice vs. Anti-Streak Design</h4>
        <p>
          Spiritual formation requires consistency (implicit in Principle 9), but streaks and gamified consistency trigger
          guilt and shame (Principle 6). The answer lies in grace-based alternatives: opt-in encouragement, celebration of
          return rather than punishment for absence, and user-initiated accountability structures.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Diagnostic Questions In Depth -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Six Diagnostic Questions — In Depth</h2>
      <p>
        These questions help you evaluate features, interactions, and design decisions in your own digital tools for
        spiritual formation:
      </p>

      <article class="principle mt-xl">
        <h4>1. Does this serve formation or engagement metrics?</h4>
        <p>
          The first question separates missional design from engagement-driven design. Ask: Is this feature built to deepen
          spiritual growth, or to maximize daily active users, session length, and retention? Formation and metrics often
          diverge. A feature that maximizes engagement may prevent actual formation. The question forces honesty about
          intent.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>2. Freedom or anxiety?</h4>
        <p>
          Spiritual formation should increase freedom. Ask: Does this feature expand the user's sense of autonomy, peace,
          and trust in God? Or does it trigger fear, obligation, or low-grade anxiety? Grace-based design (Principle 6)
          prioritizes freedom. If a feature relies on guilt or FOMO to sustain engagement, it fails this test.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>3. Will the user's motivation survive removing the feature?</h4>
        <p>
          This tests sustainability and intrinsic motivation. Ask: If you removed the notification, the streak counter, or
          the social feature, would the user continue the practice because it serves their formation? Or would engagement
          collapse? Features that serve true formation strengthen intrinsic motivation; features that rely on mechanics
          often don't. This is the test of depth.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>4. Does this honor human dignity and agency?</h4>
        <p>
          Missional design treats users as full humans with wisdom, discernment, and choice—not as optimization targets.
          Ask: Are users treated as agents of their own formation, or as subjects to be manipulated? Does the design extend
          trust, or deploy behavioral nudges? Does it honor the user's capacity to make decisions about their own spiritual
          journey?
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>5. If users developed deep communion with God and no longer needed the app, would we celebrate or mourn?</h4>
        <p>
          This inverts the typical product question. Normally, losing users is failure. In missional design, success is when
          users outgrow the app—when they've been formed so deeply that they no longer need your tools. Ask: Is the goal to
          serve the user's formation (even if it means eventual departure), or to create permanent dependency? The answer
          reveals whether the app truly serves formation or just its own sustainability.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="principle">
        <h4>6. If a user had a spiritually dry year, would they feel welcomed back or judged?</h4>
        <p>
          This tests grace. Ask: Does the system communicate that return is welcomed, or that absence is failure? Dry
          seasons are part of spiritual formation. A grace-based system honors this and creates low-friction re-entry. One
          that judges through streaks, reminders, and social comparison pushes struggling users away. This question asks
          whether the design reflects the gospel's posture toward failure and return.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How to Use the Framework -->
  <section class="section-alt section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>How to Use This Framework</h2>

      <div class="grid grid-2 mt-lg">
        <div class="card">
          <h4>For Founders & Product Leaders</h4>
          <p>
            Use these nine principles to guide feature decisions, design choices, and product strategy. Let them shape
            your philosophy before you build. Use the six diagnostic questions as a design review ritual.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h4>For Designers & Engineers</h4>
          <p>
            Apply these principles in interface design, data architecture, and interaction design. They're not constraints—they're
            liberating. They clarify what you're optimizing for beyond engagement metrics.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h4>For Churches & Ministry Leaders</h4>
          <p>
            Use this framework to evaluate digital tools you recommend to your congregation. These principles can help you
            ask better questions about whether tools serve formation or just engagement.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="card">
          <h4>For Researchers & Academics</h4>
          <p>
            This framework bridges theology, behavioral science, and product design. Use it to research digital formation,
            to challenge product assumptions, or to develop new tools grounded in missional design.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container text-center">
      <h2>Building Missional Digital Tools?</h2>
      <p class="text-muted">
        This framework is published openly as a resource for the field. If you're building technology for spiritual
        formation, I'd love to hear from you.
      </p>
      <a href="mailto:hello@treppmann.design" class="btn">Get in Touch</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .principle {
    padding: var(--spacing-lg);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-lg);
  }

  .principle h4 {
    color: var(--color-primary);
    margin-bottom: var(--spacing-md);
    margin-top: 0;
  }

  .principle p {
    margin-bottom: 0;
    color: var(--color-text-light);
  }
</style>
